{
  "text": "The picture about postconditioning cardioprotection includes now passive and active mechanisms that lead to prevention of mPTP opening and cardioprotection. Again the RISK pathway is involved [CITATION_1] (Fig. 5) . We have shown that postconditioning is NOS and guanylyl cyclase dependent [CITATION_2] . Most importantly, it has been shown that if we delay postconditioning maneuvers just for few minutes PostC is not longer protective [CITATION_3] . The relevant time-window may be species-specific and may be conditioned by concomitant diseases and by the suited end-point (infarct size, stunning or arrhythmias) [CITATION_4] .",
